Knights are heavy melee fighters trained in formation discipline and controlled coordinated aggression — the formalized inheritors of the warden tradition, produced when the Iron Reformation systematized accumulated road warden fighting knowledge into a professional officer doctrine. The transformation happened during post-Ninth Meridian eastern campaigns, when warlords found that individually skilled warden-tradition fighters repeatedly failed at siege operations requiring sustained coordination. The Compact of the Seven Chains established mutual rules of engagement and created a new officer class bound by shared doctrine regardless of which employer hired them — a political innovation enabling enemies to have adversaries who adhered to predictable engagement rules. The Compact's motto, break the line, hold the ground, leave no fallen comrade behind, encodes three commitments in productive tension: controlled aggression and forward movement; defensive discipline and position maintenance; willingness to accept casualties in recovery operations. Knight training is deliberately extended because psychological formation takes years — developing the trained reflex to maintain formation discipline under sustained casualties, unexpected maneuvers, and the pressure of holding position while allies are down. Knight academies formalized the tradition through written curricula, standardized assessment, and institutional memory that persists across practitioners, but at the cost of deep contextual specialization that Compact-era practitioner-to-practitioner mentorship achieved. The Compact's foundational principle — doctrine over employer loyalty — creates periodic tension with civic governance structures that expect their employed practitioners' institutional loyalty to be unambiguous. The Crusader adept synthesis reclaims the Solar Court's campaign-honor title, combining Knight formation discipline with Swordsman individual momentum escalation.

