Ushabti legal doctrine applied to the Compact of the Seven Chains produces a specific institutional claim: the Compact is a foundational agreement whose terms create ongoing obligations surviving the original signatories. Ushabti-trained Knights in Kowloon treat the Compact as an active legal instrument rather than historical precedent — a still-binding agreement whose terms govern institutional loyalty. This is a more legally precise version of the general Knight principle that doctrine governs over employer: a Knight who follows Compact doctrine over an employer directive is fulfilling a binding legal obligation, not making a discretionary moral choice. Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has considered but not formally adopted this argument in proceedings involving Guard conflicts.
